		<div class="comment" id="comment-6285">
	<p><cite>Comment by <a href='http://www.pixelingo.com' rel='external nofollow'>Carolyn</a> &#8212; May 05 2006 @ <a href="#comment-6285">7:47 pm</a></cite> </p>

			
	<p>@Kevin</p>
<p>There are a lot of sites that display the work of designers, some good, some great. I&#8217;d spend some time looking through them to see whose work you like. You might then look at their blogs or company sites to see what you think about their attitudes about a range of things, to see if it&#8217;s a good fit. Regarding another comment made here, to each his own, but I don&#8217;t believe in going to sites where people bid against each other. It degrades the profession and often takes advantage of desperate people who are willing to work for much, much, much less than a living wage.  It&#8217;s also how you get yourself into situations where people promise the moon for an impossibly low price&#8211;what a surprise when they can&#8217;t deliver the moon for that price! It&#8217;s just like virtually every other profession: if you want professional work, you need to pay professional prices.<br />
Now, for those sites. Look for the ones that are <acronym title="Cascading Style Sheets">CSS</acronym>-based. Your odds are much greater that the person is at least making an attempt at using web standards. Anything else is SO last century. :)<br />
<a href="http://www.cssmania.com" rel="nofollow">www.cssmania.com</a><br />
<a href="http://www.cssbeauty.com" rel="nofollow">www.cssbeauty.com</a><br />
tom.ma/screenblog<br />
<a href="http://www.stylegala.com" rel="nofollow">www.stylegala.com</a><br />
or go to forums at places like wordpress.org and watch what&#8217;s happening for awhile, or join a <acronym title="Cascading Style Sheets">CSS</acronym> discussion list. You&#8217;ll start finding people you like, and you&#8217;ll start figuring out who is smart and/or talented.<br />
Hope this helps.</p>
	</div>

